00:00:10.060 --> 00:00:11.042
-Hello, everyone.

00:00:11.042 --> 00:00:12.515
Welcome back.

00:00:12.515 --> 00:00:14.280
I hope you had a good break.

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:16.280
My name is Janet
Rich-Edwards and I

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:20.100
am one of the two science
advisers to the Radcliffe

00:00:20.100 --> 00:00:21.050
Institute here.

00:00:21.050 --> 00:00:22.800
And I want to welcome
you back for what

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:25.340
was a great start to
the program in a really

00:00:25.340 --> 00:00:28.360
interesting second panel
now focused on solutions.

00:00:28.360 --> 00:00:34.380
I'm going to introduce
Anula Jayasuriya, right?

00:00:34.380 --> 00:00:35.110
Very good.

00:00:35.110 --> 00:00:40.040
Who is the co-founder of
Evolvence India Life Science

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:42.980
Fund, founder of
Exclaim Capital,

00:00:42.980 --> 00:00:45.910
and I think possesses more
Harvard degrees than anyone

00:00:45.910 --> 00:00:48.020
I've ever met.

00:00:48.020 --> 00:00:51.000
She's going to lead us off
and moderate the second panel.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:51.990
So, welcome.

00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:53.480
-Thank you.

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:55.150
Thank you everyone
for being here.

00:00:55.150 --> 00:00:58.680
I'm especially delighted
to see so many young women.

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:01.390
And we are all hoping
that we'll be talking

00:01:01.390 --> 00:01:04.360
about is relevant for you.

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:06.580
In case you missed
the first panel,

00:01:06.580 --> 00:01:09.130
let me just go over
the outline here--

00:01:09.130 --> 00:01:11.360
is that I will speak
for a very short time,

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:14.920
each panelist will have
15 minutes to describe

00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:17.330
their vantage point,
and then there

00:01:17.330 --> 00:01:20.550
will be a Q&amp;A for 15
minutes afterwards.

00:01:20.550 --> 00:01:25.180
Please line up and state your
name and your affiliation

00:01:25.180 --> 00:01:27.800
when you ask your questions.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:30.510
So thank you for
panel number one

00:01:30.510 --> 00:01:35.780
for giving us a teaser
into panel number two

00:01:35.780 --> 00:01:38.960
as we discuss solutions.

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:43.810
And let me also first
thank Nancy Hopkins, who

00:01:43.810 --> 00:01:46.514
is the first person who
taught me about transposons

00:01:46.514 --> 00:01:48.180
and jumping genes
when I was in college.

00:01:48.180 --> 00:01:49.298
I was a Radcliffe alumni.

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:56.080
And then I read
the issue of nature

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:00.840
from 2013 where that
describes her struggle

00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:03.560
to bring light to this topic.

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:06.220
And today I'm delighted
to actually see her again

00:02:06.220 --> 00:02:06.820
in person.

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:08.030
Thank you, Nancy.

00:02:08.030 --> 00:02:10.070
And Harvard and
Radcliffe Institute,

00:02:10.070 --> 00:02:11.440
thank you for having me here.

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:21.350
Deborah gave us a suggestion
that I want to emphasize.

00:02:21.350 --> 00:02:22.390
Start practicing.

00:02:22.390 --> 00:02:23.910
Don't wait to be asked.

00:02:23.910 --> 00:02:25.430
Ask to go to the prom.

00:02:25.430 --> 00:02:27.760
Invite the person to go
to the prom with you.

00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:32.410
Don't wait to ask to be married,
ask the person to marry you.

00:02:32.410 --> 00:02:33.660
Good practice.

00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:34.290
Ask.

00:02:34.290 --> 00:02:38.130
And when you ask, expect to
see some people very surprised

00:02:38.130 --> 00:02:42.670
and not necessarily very happy,
but be resilient and stay

00:02:42.670 --> 00:02:44.260
to the point.

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:48.240
I'd also want to talk
a little bit about what

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:51.500
Allison talked about.

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:55.540
I brought a series of
articles and among them

00:02:55.540 --> 00:03:00.840
was the venture investors
prefer to fund handsome men.

00:03:03.370 --> 00:03:05.420
Maybe it was
apocryphal, but there

00:03:05.420 --> 00:03:09.680
was a follow up that said
that beautiful women were

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:12.300
the least likely to get funded.

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:18.010
And so that was another part
that was quite interesting.

00:03:18.010 --> 00:03:21.640
Then I have an
economist article that's

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:25.140
talking about the weaker sex and
they're not referring to women.

00:03:25.140 --> 00:03:27.670
They're talking about
boys and education.

00:03:27.670 --> 00:03:31.680
So the pipeline for
high achieving men,

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:37.770
or for men at the school
level is problematic, right?

00:03:37.770 --> 00:03:41.450
And it's quite the opposite
in women in college

00:03:41.450 --> 00:03:44.190
and in higher education.

00:03:44.190 --> 00:03:47.970
So that is also an
ecosystem aspect

00:03:47.970 --> 00:03:50.200
that we have to think about.

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:52.250
Now let's talk about boards.

00:03:52.250 --> 00:03:56.460
So again, this panel will
talk about it in more detail.

00:03:56.460 --> 00:04:00.110
But I think getting on
board is very important.

00:04:00.110 --> 00:04:02.570
Debra talked about
the two people.

00:04:02.570 --> 00:04:06.540
[? Helena ?] Morrissey, from the
financial services in Britain

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:08.730
is a very interesting woman.

00:04:08.730 --> 00:04:11.350
She has taken a
different point of view.

00:04:11.350 --> 00:04:14.090
You may all know about
boards in Europe,

00:04:14.090 --> 00:04:19.519
where the Nordic countries have
required a certain number quota

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:20.850
system.

00:04:20.850 --> 00:04:23.880
And she has taken a
different point of view.

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:26.650
She's calling it the 30% club.

00:04:26.650 --> 00:04:32.400
And she sees 30% of
board leadership women

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:33.970
as being the critical number.

00:04:33.970 --> 00:04:37.700
I don't know where she pull
that number out, but that is--

00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:41.350
And her strategy is
to go to powerful men

00:04:41.350 --> 00:04:45.310
in Britain, who are chair people
or chairmen of their boards.

00:04:45.310 --> 00:04:50.030
And make them recruit
the women onto the board.

00:04:50.030 --> 00:04:53.520
So she's taking a softer
sell, if you will,

00:04:53.520 --> 00:04:56.540
rather than the quota system.

00:04:56.540 --> 00:04:59.570
I hesi-- I'm of two minds about
mentioning this, which she does

00:04:59.570 --> 00:05:02.150
happen to have nine children.

00:05:02.150 --> 00:05:04.340
And she is very successful.

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:07.050
That does astound me.

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:14.410
Then another headline
here, female VCs,

00:05:14.410 --> 00:05:17.150
what do entrepreneurs
really think?

00:05:17.150 --> 00:05:19.800
So this data
suggests-- and it all

00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:22.270
comes from the power
of perception--

00:05:22.270 --> 00:05:29.900
that men and women
entrepreneurs often think

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:32.010
that male VCs have more power.

00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:36.220
So they prefer to be
funded by male VCs

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:40.310
based on this belief in power.

00:05:40.310 --> 00:05:50.610
And there is [INAUDIBLE] that
which is also that less than 5%

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:52.690
of venture
capitalists are women.

00:05:52.690 --> 00:05:56.660
And I think lots of
data on social behavior

00:05:56.660 --> 00:05:58.680
where you like what's like you.

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:02.830
And so it's also harder
for women entrepreneurs

00:06:02.830 --> 00:06:04.510
to raise money.

00:06:04.510 --> 00:06:06.400
Perhaps some part
of it has to do

00:06:06.400 --> 00:06:09.530
with it being that
it's primarily

00:06:09.530 --> 00:06:12.800
men making the decision.

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:15.600
Also something that I
think about a whole lot

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:20.080
is that it is hard for women
who are climb being the venture

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:24.900
capital ladder, which is a
delicate ladder for women.

00:06:24.900 --> 00:06:26.880
To espouse women,
because there's

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:31.260
a complex dynamic of are
you espousing these women,

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:33.650
because you're a
woman or do you really

00:06:33.650 --> 00:06:35.270
believe in their company?

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:38.350
So there are all
kinds of subtleties

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:39.880
that one should think about.

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:42.690
And this article-- we just
know this-- women are not

00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:46.320
making progress in the
male dominated VC world

00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:47.110
as data show.

00:06:47.110 --> 00:06:52.840
So right there is a
pretty pervasive bias

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:57.170
for entrepreneurship, because
the eye of the person who's

00:06:57.170 --> 00:06:58.490
making the judgment.

00:06:58.490 --> 00:07:02.210
And that brings me to the
unconscious bias world,

00:07:02.210 --> 00:07:05.240
which we will hear about here.

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:12.400
And that is that if the system
is geared towards measuring

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:15.360
one group of people
at their talents,

00:07:15.360 --> 00:07:18.530
it is fairly
unlikely to work just

00:07:18.530 --> 00:07:23.040
as well in another group that
has different characteristics.

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:25.720
And that brings me
to the economist

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:28.420
article from January
23rd this year,

00:07:28.420 --> 00:07:30.570
What's holding women back?

00:07:30.570 --> 00:07:33.670
So this study showed that
majority of Americans

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:37.340
said that they thought men and
women were equally capable.

00:07:37.340 --> 00:07:41.640
However, and so they believed
in meritocracy, democracy,

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:43.790
equality, all those
wonderful things.

00:07:43.790 --> 00:07:50.750
However, PS, when
it came to being

00:07:50.750 --> 00:07:53.980
asked would you
have a woman lead,

00:07:53.980 --> 00:07:56.170
they're using the
word viscerally.

00:07:56.170 --> 00:08:00.170
Viscerally, Americans resisted
letting femininity and power

00:08:00.170 --> 00:08:02.440
go hand in hand.

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:08.860
And that conclusion was
in our minds, we are open,

00:08:08.860 --> 00:08:11.560
but at a gut level,
which is what

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:14.570
unconscious bias taps
into, this is a very hard

00:08:14.570 --> 00:08:17.890
to leap for people to make.

00:08:17.890 --> 00:08:25.240
And then there's the aspect
of various corporations making

00:08:25.240 --> 00:08:27.200
statements, bold statements.

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:32.640
For example, Intel has
appointed Renee James

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:35.200
and given her a
$300 million budget

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:37.870
to increase corporate
diversity, a lot

00:08:37.870 --> 00:08:39.980
of it being amongst women.

00:08:39.980 --> 00:08:45.840
Now I live in Silicon Valley and
there is a lot of talk in tech,

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:49.460
not in biotech, in tech,
about getting more women

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:52.010
and there are bloggers who are
talking about it all the time.

00:08:52.010 --> 00:08:55.330
People judging companies
by their lack of women.

00:08:55.330 --> 00:08:58.050
A big spotlight.

00:08:58.050 --> 00:09:01.730
I may be just unaware,
but I don't believe quite

00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:06.530
that level of focus has
been devoted to biotech.

00:09:06.530 --> 00:09:10.230
Perhaps it's because there
are more biotech CEOs and more

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:11.930
senior women in
biotech, but that

00:09:11.930 --> 00:09:15.410
doesn't mean that
harsh light shouldn't

00:09:15.410 --> 00:09:17.050
be focused on the issue.

00:09:17.050 --> 00:09:20.330
So I think it would be
good to do something

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:23.730
that Nancy Hopkins tried to
do and should carry the baton.

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:28.190
And actually talk,
blog, talk about this,

00:09:28.190 --> 00:09:33.310
let people hear the
dissatisfaction with the status

00:09:33.310 --> 00:09:34.600
quo.

00:09:34.600 --> 00:09:39.980
And suggestions might be
to give CEOs incentives

00:09:39.980 --> 00:09:43.220
for recruiting women to board.

00:09:43.220 --> 00:09:45.870
So recruiting women
in their companies.

00:09:45.870 --> 00:09:52.840
There could be other ways to
make this more interesting.

00:09:52.840 --> 00:10:00.700
And I'd also share with
you this is an n of 1--

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:04.610
I was trained as a scientist,
but I'm now a business person

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:08.810
so I can use n of
1-- a woman who

00:10:08.810 --> 00:10:14.530
had been at Genentech
and at the FDA

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:17.840
and also is a research
scientist said to me,

00:10:17.840 --> 00:10:22.290
you know what I decided just
to start my own company.

00:10:22.290 --> 00:10:25.170
And I didn't just
start my own company,

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:30.060
I developed the relationship
with the funder.

00:10:30.060 --> 00:10:33.530
I maintained that relationship
as my relationship

00:10:33.530 --> 00:10:34.400
with the funder.

00:10:34.400 --> 00:10:39.710
So that gave me power and power
was an operative word three.

00:10:39.710 --> 00:10:42.090
So enough from me.

00:10:42.090 --> 00:10:45.380
Let me introduce our
panel very briefly.

00:10:45.380 --> 00:10:48.990
We're very, very fortunate
to have a very diverse panel

00:10:48.990 --> 00:10:51.340
representing all the
different stakeholders just

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:53.700
like panel one did.

00:10:53.700 --> 00:10:57.930
We have a policy expert,
a PhD biologist who's

00:10:57.930 --> 00:11:00.530
a venture capitalist,
and then we

00:11:00.530 --> 00:11:04.340
have Robin who is an academic.

00:11:04.340 --> 00:11:09.300
So Victoria is the
founding executive director

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:12.390
of women and public policy
at the Harvard Kennedy

00:11:12.390 --> 00:11:14.690
School of Government.

00:11:14.690 --> 00:11:20.030
Their mission led by
Victoria is gender equality

00:11:20.030 --> 00:11:24.370
to improve the lives of
women across the globe.

00:11:24.370 --> 00:11:27.910
Ann is the senior
director of investments

00:11:27.910 --> 00:11:31.090
at Sanofi-Genzyme BioVentures.

00:11:31.090 --> 00:11:35.060
She has a PhD in
systems biology from MIT

00:11:35.060 --> 00:11:37.270
and also did a post-doc.

00:11:37.270 --> 00:11:39.980
And she also went to HBS.

00:11:39.980 --> 00:11:45.410
Ann can speak to the
transition from PhD academia

00:11:45.410 --> 00:11:50.870
and also to the role that
venture capital might play.

00:11:50.870 --> 00:11:52.950
In particular corporate
venture capital,

00:11:52.950 --> 00:11:58.080
because there are two breeds
in venture capitalists and Ann

00:11:58.080 --> 00:12:00.950
represents the corporate
strategic venture capitalists,

00:12:00.950 --> 00:12:02.390
who are somewhat
different in what

00:12:02.390 --> 00:12:05.990
they look for than the
institutional venture

00:12:05.990 --> 00:12:07.050
capitalists.

00:12:07.050 --> 00:12:12.300
And then furthest away
from me is Robin Ely,

00:12:12.300 --> 00:12:16.460
she's a professor of Business
Administration at the Harvard

00:12:16.460 --> 00:12:18.020
Business School.

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:23.160
And I had to get over saying
I went to the business school.

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:26.100
And I got laughed at
a lot in California.

00:12:26.100 --> 00:12:29.300
Professor Ely will be
presenting research

00:12:29.300 --> 00:12:34.900
on how HBS is tackling
the issue of it's

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:40.440
not so previously, not so
hospitable culture for women.

00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:46.700
And Dean Nohria has taken this
on as an initiative to make HBS

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:48.700
a more inclusive environment.

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:52.900
And this has been led by Robin.

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:57.190
So we really would like to hear
your views, Robin, on ideas.

00:12:59.780 --> 00:13:05.670
We will then ask each panelist
to speak for 15 minutes

00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:06.960
and express their views.

00:13:06.960 --> 00:13:09.680
And then I will take
questions for 15 and then

00:13:09.680 --> 00:13:11.290
after that it'll be your turn.

00:13:11.290 --> 00:13:14.970
And please come up with
lots of good questions.

00:13:14.970 --> 00:13:16.560
Victoria.

00:13:16.560 --> 00:13:17.540
-Thank you so much.

00:13:21.230 --> 00:13:24.870
So we've had a really robust
conversation this morning.

00:13:24.870 --> 00:13:26.840
And our entire
conversation has really

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:30.730
focused on how do
we navigate systems.

00:13:30.730 --> 00:13:32.590
At the women public
policy program,

00:13:32.590 --> 00:13:35.750
we've been working
for nearly 20 years

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:38.660
not on measuring
where the gaps are.

00:13:38.660 --> 00:13:40.540
Tho we certainly do
some of that work,

00:13:40.540 --> 00:13:42.380
but how do we
identify and define

00:13:42.380 --> 00:13:47.380
a replicable interventions
to close those gaps.

00:13:47.380 --> 00:13:50.490
How do you determine what
the intervention will cost,

00:13:50.490 --> 00:13:54.120
how effective it is, and
where can it be applied.

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:56.630
This is a panel about
solutions and we're

00:13:56.630 --> 00:13:59.010
going to talk about
where is the edge of what

00:13:59.010 --> 00:14:02.970
we know about how solutions
work and how to implement them.

00:14:02.970 --> 00:14:06.000
My goal is over the
next 14 minutes,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:07.930
I will give you some
things that you can

00:14:07.930 --> 00:14:10.130
do within your organization.

00:14:10.130 --> 00:14:15.280
Now because we can't
immediately fix all the systems,

00:14:15.280 --> 00:14:17.890
having conversations
about how to navigate them

00:14:17.890 --> 00:14:22.500
is extraordinarily important
and impactful and needed.

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:25.179
And we today are particularly
talking about gender,

00:14:25.179 --> 00:14:26.970
but I think it's very
important to remember

00:14:26.970 --> 00:14:28.469
that what we're
really talking about

00:14:28.469 --> 00:14:32.220
is any non-traditional
actor in the system.

00:14:32.220 --> 00:14:35.120
Anyone who breaks with the
stereotypical frame and I'll

00:14:35.120 --> 00:14:38.690
talk about that and
specificity in a few moments.

00:14:38.690 --> 00:14:42.090
So we had discussion in
the earlier panel about how

00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:44.170
are women leaders perceived.

00:14:44.170 --> 00:14:48.970
This is Heidi Roizen, CEO
formerly of a very significant

00:14:48.970 --> 00:14:50.180
tech firm.

00:14:50.180 --> 00:14:53.170
There is a case written
about her for HBS.

00:14:53.170 --> 00:14:56.330
And some of Robin's
colleagues thought, you now

00:14:56.330 --> 00:14:59.100
our students are reacting
to this case in such a way

00:14:59.100 --> 00:15:01.710
that it really gives us pause.

00:15:01.710 --> 00:15:04.880
And they decided to take
this case about Heidi

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:10.010
and substitute Howard for Heidi.

00:15:10.010 --> 00:15:12.660
And very similar to what
Allison talked about where

00:15:12.660 --> 00:15:16.210
nothing else changes.

00:15:16.210 --> 00:15:18.530
And it's a beautiful
experiment, right?

00:15:18.530 --> 00:15:20.780
Because we have students
that we can put in one place,

00:15:20.780 --> 00:15:22.120
and students we
can put in another.

00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:23.619
We can change it
over a time period,

00:15:23.619 --> 00:15:25.800
but keep everything the same.

00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:30.540
And what they found is when
the behaviors are identical,

00:15:30.540 --> 00:15:33.890
people like Howard more.

