what they view is male tasks.

00:26:06.300 --> 00:26:10.050
What tasks are male and
female are defined by culture?

00:26:10.050 --> 00:26:13.660
There is nothing
innate about them.

00:26:13.660 --> 00:26:17.470
And we know this, because they
vary by culture, by region,

00:26:17.470 --> 00:26:21.650
by time period, but we don't
like breaking that gender

00:26:21.650 --> 00:26:22.870
stereotype.

00:26:22.870 --> 00:26:26.240
So what we know-- moving
on to a terrific paper

00:26:26.240 --> 00:26:30.460
by WaPPPs director, Iris
Bohnet and her colleagues,

00:26:30.460 --> 00:26:32.960
Max Bazerman and
Alexander van Geen,

00:26:32.960 --> 00:26:38.320
is that when we look at one off
hires and one off promotions,

00:26:38.320 --> 00:26:42.530
the nontraditional
candidate does very poorly.

00:26:42.530 --> 00:26:46.230
One offs are never measured
against another live person.

00:26:46.230 --> 00:26:50.230
They're measured against
a fictitious norm.

00:26:50.230 --> 00:26:55.860
It is really hard to
be the fictitious norm.

00:26:55.860 --> 00:26:57.690
Really hard.

00:26:57.690 --> 00:27:01.000
So what happens is when you
compare more than one candidate

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.730
and you can easily
build processes

00:27:03.730 --> 00:27:06.260
within companies where you
look at multiple people

00:27:06.260 --> 00:27:09.360
at a stage or time period.

00:27:09.360 --> 00:27:11.360
And I say time period
because you can't always

00:27:11.360 --> 00:27:15.150
make that higher promotion in
multiple departments at once,

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:17.840
but you can look back
over time to compare

00:27:17.840 --> 00:27:20.640
against other former candidates.

00:27:20.640 --> 00:27:25.380
And once you're looking at
real data, the effect of bias

00:27:25.380 --> 00:27:28.370
goes away.

00:27:28.370 --> 00:27:31.880
Then we begin to compare
Janet's performance

00:27:31.880 --> 00:27:35.550
with Rebecca's performance, or
Janet's performance with John's

00:27:35.550 --> 00:27:38.710
performance, and
women do very well

00:27:38.710 --> 00:27:42.510
with no bias effect, which
by the way is a huge finding.

00:27:42.510 --> 00:27:47.455
We would expect at most it would
be mitigated but not go away.

00:27:47.455 --> 00:27:49.580
And I have lots of other
things I could go through,

00:27:49.580 --> 00:27:51.330
but we're going to
skip all that and we're

00:27:51.330 --> 00:27:54.490
going to jump to policy
making for a moment.

