01:37:06.660 --> 01:37:08.530
Thank you to all
the speakers today.

01:37:08.530 --> 01:37:11.350
We've heard multiple
times today about how

01:37:11.350 --> 01:37:14.000
women experience marriage
and motherhood differently

01:37:14.000 --> 01:37:15.800
than men in the workplace.

01:37:15.800 --> 01:37:18.389
And I've seen a lot of data
recently about millennials

01:37:18.389 --> 01:37:20.430
and younger generations
are ranking this as a lot

01:37:20.430 --> 01:37:23.000
less important to
them for their future.

01:37:23.000 --> 01:37:25.790
So my question is, what
is a situation currently

01:37:25.790 --> 01:37:27.950
for women who were unmarried
or don't have kids?

01:37:27.950 --> 01:37:29.491
And how do you think
that will change

01:37:29.491 --> 01:37:32.230
as that demographic grows?

01:37:32.230 --> 01:37:36.960
-Do you have any
data on this topic?

01:37:36.960 --> 01:37:40.840
-Well, I thought you were
going to go someplace else.

01:37:40.840 --> 01:37:48.240
What I've seen, first of all,
is that companies are not--

01:37:48.240 --> 01:37:51.710
they're not oriented to
recognizing or supporting

01:37:51.710 --> 01:38:00.517
men's very strong commitments
to actually being caretakers

01:38:00.517 --> 01:38:01.600
and not just breadwinners.

01:38:01.600 --> 01:38:04.520
So I just want to say that,
I think if you actually

01:38:04.520 --> 01:38:08.080
look at what people's experience
is, men are having a very

01:38:08.080 --> 01:38:10.770
hard time, not just
millennials are having

01:38:10.770 --> 01:38:14.309
a very hard time managing
the requirements meant

01:38:14.309 --> 01:38:16.225
for professionals that
they be available 24/7.

01:38:18.970 --> 01:38:21.040
I think what I've
seen in my research

01:38:21.040 --> 01:38:25.950
on this among single
women is that it's

01:38:25.950 --> 01:38:30.350
almost as if the
organization is sort of set

01:38:30.350 --> 01:38:34.850
up almost not to recognize the
possibility of single women

01:38:34.850 --> 01:38:36.530
or women without children.

01:38:36.530 --> 01:38:38.830
And so women do--
they do it's just

01:38:38.830 --> 01:38:40.716
kind of get grouped together.

01:38:40.716 --> 01:38:42.340
It's sort of like
that's who women are.

01:38:42.340 --> 01:38:44.260
They're understood
as someone who

01:38:44.260 --> 01:38:47.700
will be either is a mother and
that means a certain thing,

01:38:47.700 --> 01:38:52.490
or who will and wants to
be and will be a mother.

01:38:52.490 --> 01:38:54.940
But your question was, what
do you do about that, right?

01:38:54.940 --> 01:38:55.440
Yeah.

01:39:03.210 --> 01:39:04.360
-I have an answer to that.

01:39:04.360 --> 01:39:04.860
-Great.

01:39:04.860 --> 01:39:06.112
-If you want.

01:39:06.112 --> 01:39:08.320
-I was about to come up with
something, but go ahead.

01:39:08.320 --> 01:39:08.820
-OK, no, no.

01:39:08.820 --> 01:39:11.140
And if you have come up with
something, interrupt me.

01:39:11.140 --> 01:39:12.098
-Yeah, I'll keep that--

01:39:12.098 --> 01:39:13.580
-Completely.

01:39:13.580 --> 01:39:15.920
So one, what we know is
narrative is really powerful.

01:39:15.920 --> 01:39:17.670
And there's going to
be a narrative, which

01:39:17.670 --> 01:39:19.545
is laid on you, which
is probably inaccurate.

01:39:19.545 --> 01:39:22.010
And I love the way Robin
refers to it is irrational,

01:39:22.010 --> 01:39:23.136
because it is.

01:39:23.136 --> 01:39:25.260
So what you have to do is
understand the narrative,

01:39:25.260 --> 01:39:26.160
which is laid on you.

01:39:26.160 --> 01:39:29.050
And the narrative is if you have
a child, even if your behaviors

01:39:29.050 --> 01:39:32.410
change in no way, you are
viewed as less committed,

01:39:32.410 --> 01:39:37.920
less engaged, your pathway to
promotion virtually disappears.

01:39:37.920 --> 01:39:40.090
And the guy down the
hall does better.

01:39:40.090 --> 01:39:42.874
But once you know that,
then you know what to do.

01:39:42.874 --> 01:39:44.290
And the way you
inoculate yourself

01:39:44.290 --> 01:39:47.110
from that is when
you're on leave

01:39:47.110 --> 01:39:49.230
you have touch points
with your manager.

01:39:49.230 --> 01:39:52.080
When you return you go in front
of them and you say, I'm here,

01:39:52.080 --> 01:39:54.280
I'm looking, what's my
next stretch assignment,

01:39:54.280 --> 01:39:58.350
which teams am I going to be
on, which programs, projects

01:39:58.350 --> 01:40:00.050
am I running?

01:40:00.050 --> 01:40:01.160
And you define it.

01:40:01.160 --> 01:40:03.490
Now people will presume
whenever they can't see you

01:40:03.490 --> 01:40:04.895
that you're with your child.

01:40:04.895 --> 01:40:07.650
It's bananas, but that's
what they presume.

01:40:07.650 --> 01:40:10.450
So you have to have
a narrative where you

01:40:10.450 --> 01:40:12.980
create an open schedule, right?

01:40:12.980 --> 01:40:14.300
You paste it on your door.

01:40:14.300 --> 01:40:16.690
You tell your colleagues,
I'm going down

01:40:16.690 --> 01:40:20.270
the hall to negotiate a deal.

01:40:20.270 --> 01:40:21.770
You have to be explicit.

01:40:21.770 --> 01:40:24.860
And much of what this work
is when you understand

01:40:24.860 --> 01:40:27.380
the cultural archetype
that's pasted on you,

01:40:27.380 --> 01:40:29.450
you have to do the
work of peeling it off.

01:40:29.450 --> 01:40:31.850
You have to tell
people who you are.

01:40:31.850 --> 01:40:33.640
I'm organizationally committed.

01:40:33.640 --> 01:40:38.020
I love being here till
9 o'clock at night.

01:40:38.020 --> 01:40:39.387
And to do it authentically.

01:40:39.387 --> 01:40:40.720
That's the other thing I'll say.

01:40:40.720 --> 01:40:42.231
This is not a game
of showmanship.

01:40:42.231 --> 01:40:44.480
This is a game of authentically
presenting and letting

01:40:44.480 --> 01:40:45.750
people see you.

01:40:45.750 --> 01:40:47.290
-Robin, do you have
a quick comment?

01:40:47.290 --> 01:40:49.040
-Well, I guess I understood
the question-- maybe,

01:40:49.040 --> 01:40:49.970
maybe I misunderstood.

01:40:49.970 --> 01:40:53.900
I thought you were saying
that as a single woman what--

01:40:53.900 --> 01:40:59.512
and yeah and not necessarily
anticipating that you're

01:40:59.512 --> 01:41:00.720
going to be in that category.

01:41:00.720 --> 01:41:04.182
But right now you
don't have the child.

01:41:04.182 --> 01:41:05.640
You don't have and
yet you're going

01:41:05.640 --> 01:41:08.422
to be perceived as someone who
is going to go down that path.

01:41:08.422 --> 01:41:09.630
So how do you deal with that.

01:41:09.630 --> 01:41:13.900
I mean, in some ways I would say
something similar to Victoria

01:41:13.900 --> 01:41:19.210
said, which is, I think you
got to resist the pressure.

01:41:19.210 --> 01:41:22.130
I mean, be aware that that
is a stereotype that's

01:41:22.130 --> 01:41:24.330
going to be put on you.

01:41:24.330 --> 01:41:29.980
And I think, creating your own
story and telling that story.

01:41:29.980 --> 01:41:35.200
I guess what I would be
concerned about is I see that

01:41:35.200 --> 01:41:37.626
there can be a kind of
a division among women

01:41:37.626 --> 01:41:39.750
in the work place-- between
women who have children

01:41:39.750 --> 01:41:41.280
and women who don't.

01:41:41.280 --> 01:41:44.750
And so I would just
maybe want to say,

01:41:44.750 --> 01:41:47.680
you know women find themselves
in different situations

01:41:47.680 --> 01:41:49.050
for all kinds of reasons.

01:41:49.050 --> 01:41:50.780
Having or not having
children is one.

01:41:50.780 --> 01:41:54.120
Being partnered and partnered in
different ways is another one.

01:41:54.120 --> 01:41:57.160
But I think it's really
important to-- even

01:41:57.160 --> 01:42:00.800
while you're differentiating
yourself and saying,

01:42:00.800 --> 01:42:03.930
this is who I am, these
are my commitments,

01:42:03.930 --> 01:42:06.960
this is what I'm willing
to do-- to not lose

01:42:06.960 --> 01:42:09.790
the connection to women who
are doing something different.

01:42:09.790 --> 01:42:10.350
-Thank you.

01:42:10.350 --> 01:42:12.060
-Nancy.

01:42:12.060 --> 01:42:13.235
-Hi, I'm Nancy Hopkins.

01:42:13.235 --> 01:42:15.890
I'm a retired professor
of biology from MIT.

01:42:15.890 --> 01:42:17.900
And I'd like to thank
the Radcliffe Institute

01:42:17.900 --> 01:42:19.630
for doing this
fantastic symposium,

01:42:19.630 --> 01:42:21.650
the wonderful panelists.

01:42:21.650 --> 01:42:24.610
I was totally depressed to hear
how much money women aren't

01:42:24.610 --> 01:42:27.620
raking in.

01:42:27.620 --> 01:42:29.190
-Me, too.

01:42:29.190 --> 01:42:30.300
-Really sad.

01:42:30.300 --> 01:42:32.650
But I'm even sadder,
actually, about the impact

01:42:32.650 --> 01:42:35.150
this has within the
universities on the women

01:42:35.150 --> 01:42:37.870
who were interested
in biology, including

01:42:37.870 --> 01:42:41.835
having really brilliant young
women literally break down

01:42:41.835 --> 01:42:44.310
in your office and say the
men go off into their office

01:42:44.310 --> 01:42:46.389
with the young men in
their labs and talk

01:42:46.389 --> 01:42:47.930
about the biotech
companies and leave

01:42:47.930 --> 01:42:49.570
the women sitting outside.

01:42:49.570 --> 01:42:52.300
So we've talked about how
the women should change,

01:42:52.300 --> 01:42:54.990
and we've talked about what
the companies might do,

01:42:54.990 --> 01:42:59.080
so I'd like to ask anyone
who's willing to answer it

01:42:59.080 --> 01:43:00.630
what should the universities do?

01:43:00.630 --> 01:43:01.880
What is the responsibility?

01:43:01.880 --> 01:43:04.880
It's not an accident that
this industry has grown up

01:43:04.880 --> 01:43:06.670
around these universities.

01:43:06.670 --> 01:43:07.950
Same for Stanford.

01:43:07.950 --> 01:43:13.840
And so, in a sense, I feel that
there's some responsibility

01:43:13.840 --> 01:43:15.070
there.

01:43:15.070 --> 01:43:17.830
Wonder what you
think about that.

01:43:17.830 --> 01:43:20.780
How they could step in
to fix this problem.

01:43:20.780 --> 01:43:22.760
-I'll just give you
one example that I

01:43:22.760 --> 01:43:25.560
thought was very compelling
that came from Berkeley.

01:43:25.560 --> 01:43:28.160
And Berkeley is not
looking at gender,

01:43:28.160 --> 01:43:29.910
but is looking at the
reality that they're

01:43:29.910 --> 01:43:33.150
aren't postdoc positions
and faculty positions.

01:43:33.150 --> 01:43:35.900
And they have started
having symposia

01:43:35.900 --> 01:43:40.640
on campus very frequently for
their postdocs and PhD Students

01:43:40.640 --> 01:43:43.710
to meet industry and
venture capitalist.

01:43:43.710 --> 01:43:46.500
-I think when it comes
to intellectual property,

01:43:46.500 --> 01:43:50.500
each discipline define--
its very fascinating.

01:43:50.500 --> 01:43:53.320
You know what you do as
an engineer the university

01:43:53.320 --> 01:43:54.930
owns forever.

01:43:54.930 --> 01:43:57.980
What you do and
things-- you know,

01:43:57.980 --> 01:44:00.310
like anything having
to do with biomedical,

01:44:00.310 --> 01:44:04.420
it appears that one
can take it with you.

01:44:04.420 --> 01:44:09.540
I don't know enough about how
the OGC manages or does this,

01:44:09.540 --> 01:44:14.519
but my thought is--
what would it take?

01:44:14.519 --> 01:44:15.810
I think we all understand that.

01:44:15.810 --> 01:44:18.680
It would take the
senior tenured faculty

01:44:18.680 --> 01:44:23.890
to put enormous pressure
having-- I'm so aware now

01:44:23.890 --> 01:44:24.890
that we're cameraed.

01:44:24.890 --> 01:44:28.490
You know, conversation
you know thoughtfully,

01:44:28.490 --> 01:44:31.130
with the corporation
about what this looks like

01:44:31.130 --> 01:44:34.410
and what it means, I'm
fascinated by your thought

01:44:34.410 --> 01:44:36.650
about Title IX and Title VII.

01:44:36.650 --> 01:44:41.220
And I think that
is really Title IX

01:44:41.220 --> 01:44:44.994
and Title VII are being looked
at and actioned right now

01:44:44.994 --> 01:44:46.910
in a way they haven't
done before that there's

01:44:46.910 --> 01:44:50.190
all kinds of growing
efficacy there.

01:44:50.190 --> 01:44:53.570
-And do you think that there
should be a regulation applied

01:44:53.570 --> 01:44:54.920
to the space?

01:44:54.920 --> 01:44:57.830
Is that a good way to
deal with the problem?

01:44:57.830 --> 01:44:58.830
-The problem is real.

01:44:58.830 --> 01:45:02.370
-I think I'll make
an observation.

01:45:02.370 --> 01:45:05.420
So someone's got to
take out the license.

01:45:05.420 --> 01:45:08.210
So it's either
the entrepreneur--

01:45:08.210 --> 01:45:10.880
these days in Boston a
lot of the venture firms

01:45:10.880 --> 01:45:12.867
are engaged in the
early stage formation,

01:45:12.867 --> 01:45:14.450
and the venture firms
are the ones who

01:45:14.450 --> 01:45:17.530
take out the license
from the university.

01:45:17.530 --> 01:45:22.420
I wonder what would happen if
the simple question were asked,

01:45:22.420 --> 01:45:26.250
can you describe for me the
composition on the diversity

01:45:26.250 --> 01:45:29.500
basis of your
venture firm or who's

01:45:29.500 --> 01:45:32.850
going to be responsible for
developing whatever you're

01:45:32.850 --> 01:45:34.750
licensing out?

01:45:34.750 --> 01:45:38.480
Because we have
data in we believe

01:45:38.480 --> 01:45:42.130
that you're more
likely to be successful

01:45:42.130 --> 01:45:45.480
if you have a diverse team.

01:45:45.480 --> 01:45:49.440
So I'm not sure about
from a policy standpoint,

01:45:49.440 --> 01:45:52.860
but I think the
venture firms that I

01:45:52.860 --> 01:45:56.935
know in town-- one
of the venture firms,

01:45:56.935 --> 01:45:58.060
actually, on their website.

01:45:58.060 --> 01:45:58.634
It was great.

01:45:58.634 --> 01:46:00.050
I haven't looked
at it in a while,

01:46:00.050 --> 01:46:02.920
because I don't look
at, because I know them.

01:46:02.920 --> 01:46:06.390
And I was surprised to see
that there are a bunch of women

01:46:06.390 --> 01:46:07.240
on the website.

01:46:07.240 --> 01:46:09.120
And I was like what?

01:46:09.120 --> 01:46:11.465
Who are these people?

01:46:11.465 --> 01:46:13.590
I have never encountered
them when I see these guys

01:46:13.590 --> 01:46:16.120
on like multiple times a basis.

01:46:16.120 --> 01:46:18.765
And they had actually
put up all their admins.

01:46:22.410 --> 01:46:24.835
Anyway, sorry
sidebar and perhaps

01:46:24.835 --> 01:46:26.460
I should have turned
off my microphone.

01:46:26.460 --> 01:46:28.755
-That is actually a very
common practice in VC firm--

01:46:28.755 --> 01:46:30.880
-Should have turned off my
microphone for that one,

01:46:30.880 --> 01:46:33.570
but I can't imagine what
would that conversation

01:46:33.570 --> 01:46:37.000
look like even if it wasn't a
policy if the simple question

01:46:37.000 --> 01:46:40.960
we're asked, can you tell me
about the diversity of the team

01:46:40.960 --> 01:46:44.440
that's responsible for
making good on the license

01:46:44.440 --> 01:46:45.890
I'm about to give you.

01:46:45.890 --> 01:46:48.380
Because we have
data and we believe

01:46:48.380 --> 01:46:49.960
it's more likely
to be successful

01:46:49.960 --> 01:46:51.850
if you have a diverse group.

01:46:51.850 --> 01:46:54.070
That's where I might just
start the conversation,

01:46:54.070 --> 01:46:58.620
because someone might
just take notice.

01:46:58.620 --> 01:46:59.450
-Thank you, Ann.

01:46:59.450 --> 01:47:00.940
It's good answer.

01:47:00.940 --> 01:47:01.460
-Great.

01:47:01.460 --> 01:47:02.439
Thank you all so much.

01:47:02.439 --> 01:47:03.480
My name's Theresa Nelson.

01:47:03.480 --> 01:47:06.630
I'm a professor in the School
of Management at Simmons College

01:47:06.630 --> 01:47:09.530
and really glad to be here.

01:47:09.530 --> 01:47:12.820
I'm going to sort of
resonate to Ann's point

01:47:12.820 --> 01:47:15.510
about the strength
of biotech in Boston.

01:47:15.510 --> 01:47:19.130
And what an important factor
it is that we are here

01:47:19.130 --> 01:47:22.480
and this is happening right
here as a world standard.

01:47:22.480 --> 01:47:24.500
And also referring to
her comment about the

01:47:24.500 --> 01:47:26.980
get it done, because
there's a group

01:47:26.980 --> 01:47:30.050
of people here across
the ecosystem in academia

01:47:30.050 --> 01:47:33.000
and entrepreneurs and
venture capitalists, who

01:47:33.000 --> 01:47:36.250
would like to take some
action around this topic.

01:47:36.250 --> 01:47:39.210
And we've been talking about
it for about two years.

01:47:39.210 --> 01:47:41.240
And what we've
come up with we're

01:47:41.240 --> 01:47:43.900
going to begin to actualize,
I believe, in the spring.

01:47:43.900 --> 01:47:46.730
And would love to get
people's senses of it.

01:47:46.730 --> 01:47:52.320
And it really has to do
with understanding the fact

01:47:52.320 --> 01:47:55.050
that the pipeline as
Nancy said in biology

01:47:55.050 --> 01:47:58.600
and academic medicine,
is so strong with women.

01:47:58.600 --> 01:48:00.420
What an enormous
achievement this

01:48:00.420 --> 01:48:03.260
is compared to 20
and 25 years ago,

01:48:03.260 --> 01:48:05.720
referring to
Victoria's comments.

01:48:05.720 --> 01:48:09.740
And we have been
wondering whether women

01:48:09.740 --> 01:48:13.860
in the early stages of their
PhDs as well as PhD students,

01:48:13.860 --> 01:48:16.990
postdocs, and those in
early science careers

01:48:16.990 --> 01:48:20.420
are really aware of their
career options in terms

01:48:20.420 --> 01:48:23.340
of commercialization; in
terms of the protection

01:48:23.340 --> 01:48:26.740
of their intellectual property;
in terms of licensing.

01:48:26.740 --> 01:48:30.120
Where is the expert in that
for them to reach out to?

01:48:30.120 --> 01:48:32.740
And to really
understand that they

01:48:32.740 --> 01:48:35.530
have choices to make
around commercialization.

01:48:35.530 --> 01:48:38.010
So we're imagining
this has to be

01:48:38.010 --> 01:48:41.190
something that happens
outside of the major teaching

01:48:41.190 --> 01:48:42.750
institutions.

01:48:42.750 --> 01:48:46.870
Perhaps and that this is a way
to really start a question so

01:48:46.870 --> 01:48:50.800
that women in science have
enough of the business

01:48:50.800 --> 01:48:53.510
entrepreneurship side as well.

01:48:53.510 --> 01:48:56.230
And so I just love to get
your thoughts on that.

01:48:59.225 --> 01:49:01.600
-Theresa, are you going to be
around for a glass of wine?

01:49:04.604 --> 01:49:05.450
-OK.

01:49:05.450 --> 01:49:06.630
Thank you for your patience.

01:49:06.630 --> 01:49:08.400
This is the last question.

01:49:08.400 --> 01:49:10.584
Yes, I was acknowledging
you and saying,

01:49:10.584 --> 01:49:11.750
thank you for your patience.

01:49:11.750 --> 01:49:12.249
-OK.

01:49:12.249 --> 01:49:15.660
I'm Cassandra Smith.

01:49:15.660 --> 01:49:18.090
This morning, I
don't remember who

01:49:18.090 --> 01:49:21.950
said it, but alluded
to the fact that women

01:49:21.950 --> 01:49:25.050
have more choices than men.

01:49:25.050 --> 01:49:30.980
But they were referring
to children not to adults.

01:49:30.980 --> 01:49:34.460
And my observation
is actually women

01:49:34.460 --> 01:49:40.140
have a much narrower
cone of acceptability

01:49:40.140 --> 01:49:43.120
in behavior than men.

01:49:43.120 --> 01:49:47.470
And in fact, again,
it's my observations

01:49:47.470 --> 01:49:51.550
that women are-- if they
kind of step out of this--

01:49:51.550 --> 01:49:58.360
are much more subjected to
criticism or corrections.

01:49:58.360 --> 01:50:02.540
And I think that's
what influences women

01:50:02.540 --> 01:50:06.150
from speaking for instance
at faculty meetings

01:50:06.150 --> 01:50:10.120
or at meetings like this.

01:50:10.120 --> 01:50:12.180
So any comments.

01:50:12.180 --> 01:50:15.900
Because the only comments
thus far in the meeting

01:50:15.900 --> 01:50:17.990
were on young children.

01:50:17.990 --> 01:50:22.840
That women, females, girls
have more choices than boys.

01:50:22.840 --> 01:50:25.750
-I think it's actually
true for adults, too.

01:50:25.750 --> 01:50:27.260
But it's a little
bit complicated.

01:50:27.260 --> 01:50:32.170
I think the research suggests
that men will be punished more

01:50:32.170 --> 01:50:34.670
for violating the
masculine stereotype

01:50:34.670 --> 01:50:37.800
and evidencing
feminine behavior.

01:50:37.800 --> 01:50:41.210
And women are punished less.

01:50:41.210 --> 01:50:45.400
They're punished, but it is
more of a violation for men

01:50:45.400 --> 01:50:46.670
to go in that direction.

01:50:46.670 --> 01:50:48.554
So I think that's true
of adults as well.

01:50:48.554 --> 01:50:50.220
I think what you're
probably noticing is

01:50:50.220 --> 01:50:55.510
that the domains within
which women are circumscribed

01:50:55.510 --> 01:50:57.270
are these public ones.

01:50:57.270 --> 01:50:59.720
And so we see it and
that's what we're all here

01:50:59.720 --> 01:51:02.530
being concerned about.

01:51:02.530 --> 01:51:04.940
But I think if you looked
at men's violations

01:51:04.940 --> 01:51:07.680
in the other direction, it's
just doesn't tend to be public.

01:51:07.680 --> 01:51:10.080
And when it is public, it's
pretty severely punished.

01:51:10.080 --> 01:51:13.220
And there's a lot of man
on man sexual harassment

01:51:13.220 --> 01:51:17.161
and violations of
gender roles-- those

01:51:17.161 --> 01:51:18.910
are the people who end
up getting sexually

01:51:18.910 --> 01:51:21.580
harassed, both men and women.

01:51:21.580 --> 01:51:23.600
But I think it's
not just children.

01:51:23.600 --> 01:51:25.020
But that's my--

01:51:25.020 --> 01:51:25.770
-Thank you, Robin.

01:51:25.770 --> 01:51:28.600
We are 15 minutes over
so we really must stop.

01:51:28.600 --> 01:51:29.930
And Janet, please.

01:51:29.930 --> 01:51:30.540
-I'll just--

01:51:30.540 --> 01:51:34.460
-Thank you, let me just thank
the panel and Janet will--

01:51:34.460 --> 01:51:36.020
and thank the
audience, thank you

01:51:36.020 --> 01:51:39.035
audience for hanging
in there for so long.

01:51:39.035 --> 01:51:40.454
And Janet, please.

01:51:40.454 --> 01:51:42.870
-I want to thank you all, thank
the panel, and the earlier

01:51:42.870 --> 01:51:44.040
panel.

01:51:44.040 --> 01:51:46.890
This is an incredibly
interesting day,

01:51:46.890 --> 01:51:48.540
even if you're not in biotech.

01:51:48.540 --> 01:51:51.244
I think you can really
see the biotech leadership

01:51:51.244 --> 01:51:52.160
and the biotech board.

01:51:52.160 --> 01:51:56.250
It's something of a litmus
test where gender relations

01:51:56.250 --> 01:51:57.920
stand in our society.

01:51:57.920 --> 01:52:02.390
This is an industry that
is less than 50 years old.

01:52:02.390 --> 01:52:04.510
And you could argue
that it's leaders

01:52:04.510 --> 01:52:09.420
are of an age where they
should know better than this.

01:52:09.420 --> 01:52:14.040
And yet, it is one of the
biggest, most lavish boys clubs

01:52:14.040 --> 01:52:15.480
we have around.

01:52:15.480 --> 01:52:18.360
So I am glad on many levels
that we've come here together

01:52:18.360 --> 01:52:20.240
to talk about it.

01:52:20.240 --> 01:52:23.180
Today we've highlighted
the bias, the gender bias,

01:52:23.180 --> 01:52:26.210
the irrational, the
implicit bias that

01:52:26.210 --> 01:52:27.950
underlies much of that.

01:52:27.950 --> 01:52:30.500
I'm very grateful for
Allison's data, which

01:52:30.500 --> 01:52:34.430
are profoundly disturbing
is still validating

01:52:34.430 --> 01:52:37.820
because it really reflects what
many of us still do experience.

01:52:37.820 --> 01:52:40.480
We've also talked about
the internal conflicts

01:52:40.480 --> 01:52:42.080
that women highlight and site.

01:52:42.080 --> 01:52:44.770
Family is priority
in that conflict.

01:52:44.770 --> 01:52:48.700
We talked a bit about
pulling way back

01:52:48.700 --> 01:52:51.590
and seeing that not
necessarily as simply

01:52:51.590 --> 01:52:56.420
the choices of individual
women but as systems problems.

01:52:56.420 --> 01:52:59.010
You'll remember the phrase
the personal is political.

01:52:59.010 --> 01:53:01.590
The personal is corporate.

01:53:01.590 --> 01:53:04.429
These are systems
design problems.

01:53:04.429 --> 01:53:06.470
We've also highlighted
some of the behaviors that

01:53:06.470 --> 01:53:09.570
might be necessary
for women success--

01:53:09.570 --> 01:53:12.200
demanding, giving time,
perhaps volunteering,

01:53:12.200 --> 01:53:15.460
tilting your head,
and also the conflict

01:53:15.460 --> 01:53:19.040
between what may be the
behaviors and the affect

01:53:19.040 --> 01:53:22.310
needed for survival versus
that which is ultimately

01:53:22.310 --> 01:53:24.370
needed for success.

01:53:24.370 --> 01:53:29.420
I think this adds up to
the danger of almost a John

01:53:29.420 --> 01:53:30.630
Henryism.

01:53:30.630 --> 01:53:32.640
Those of you who
are sociologists

01:53:32.640 --> 01:53:33.780
will recognize that term.

01:53:33.780 --> 01:53:36.890
It was coined by Sherman
James to describe the attitude

01:53:36.890 --> 01:53:39.150
among some minority
citizens that they

01:53:39.150 --> 01:53:42.690
have to work harder to
get to the same place

01:53:42.690 --> 01:53:44.250
the majority citizens do.

01:53:44.250 --> 01:53:48.910
Even if it comes at a
cost to their health.

01:53:48.910 --> 01:53:51.340
The reference is to
a tail, a folktale

01:53:51.340 --> 01:53:54.850
about an African American
railroad man, a steel driver,

01:53:54.850 --> 01:53:58.610
who vowed that he could beat the
steam engine with his muscles

01:53:58.610 --> 01:54:03.050
and with his hammer to drive
a tunnel through a mountain.

01:54:03.050 --> 01:54:07.070
And he went up against the
steam engine and dammit he won,

01:54:07.070 --> 01:54:10.350
but he died with a
hammer in his hand.

01:54:10.350 --> 01:54:14.150
I would say that the modern
day equivalent is that bad ass

01:54:14.150 --> 01:54:16.502
woman who's working two shifts.

01:54:16.502 --> 01:54:18.210
She's working all day
at the biotech firm

01:54:18.210 --> 01:54:20.660
and she's going home to
work with her family.

01:54:20.660 --> 01:54:22.610
She may get to that
C-suite but she's

01:54:22.610 --> 01:54:24.650
got a briefcase on one
shoulder and a diaper bag

01:54:24.650 --> 01:54:26.040
on the other shoulder.

01:54:26.040 --> 01:54:31.830
It describes the
way it is, but it

01:54:31.830 --> 01:54:35.720
doesn't have to describe
the way it should be.

01:54:35.720 --> 01:54:38.480
I think we've talked
about making changes.

01:54:38.480 --> 01:54:42.820
It isn't just about navigating
the system or fixing the women,

01:54:42.820 --> 01:54:45.140
but really about
changing the system.

01:54:45.140 --> 01:54:48.020
We've talked about really
making clear the value

01:54:48.020 --> 01:54:51.390
proposition of having
women who stay,

01:54:51.390 --> 01:54:53.139
inviting women in
having them stay.

01:54:53.139 --> 01:54:54.680
The burden of proof,
unfortunately, I

01:54:54.680 --> 01:54:56.590
think is on us.

01:54:56.590 --> 01:54:58.450
We're the minority
in the situation,

01:54:58.450 --> 01:55:01.370
we need to make that case,
we need to make it clearly.

01:55:01.370 --> 01:55:03.310
We've talked about
change we must make.

01:55:03.310 --> 01:55:06.650
We've talked about how that is
deep, ongoing, transformational

01:55:06.650 --> 01:55:08.670
work to use Robin's phrase.

01:55:08.670 --> 01:55:11.520
And we need to define what
is actionable change that we

01:55:11.520 --> 01:55:13.240
can demand.

01:55:13.240 --> 01:55:15.560
I'll just finish by
saying at the break I need

01:55:15.560 --> 01:55:18.790
to draft these remarks so I went
out back in the hallway there

01:55:18.790 --> 01:55:21.010
and a young woman
who I couldn't see

01:55:21.010 --> 01:55:22.720
was out there too
clearly calling

01:55:22.720 --> 01:55:25.410
her partner about-- looks
like this conference is

01:55:25.410 --> 01:55:29.170
going to go long, can you
pick Alexandra up at daycare.

01:55:29.170 --> 01:55:31.250
I didn't see you, I don't
know if you're here.

01:55:31.250 --> 01:55:33.174
-That was me.

01:55:33.174 --> 01:55:34.136
-Oh, that was you?

01:55:38.465 --> 01:55:41.170
I was going to say as
I hope whoever you are,

01:55:41.170 --> 01:55:43.190
you're still here,
because we need you.

01:55:43.190 --> 01:55:47.060
We need every one of you,
we need you and your talent.

01:55:47.060 --> 01:55:50.180
So thank you for being here.

